//     "content": "## The problem\n\nMost social service organisations collect a lot of data. Case notes, intake forms, programme attendance, volunteer hours — the list goes on. But very few of them can answer a simple question on the spot: *is our work making a difference?*\n\nThis isn't a data problem. It's an infrastructure problem.\n\n## What I found at TOUCH\n\nWhen I joined the Technology & Innovation team, we had data in at least six different systems, none of which talked to each other. Reports were built manually in Excel every quarter. By the time a report landed on a manager's desk, the data was three months old.\n\n## What we built\n\nWe built an end-to-end analytics pipeline — ingesting data from multiple source systems, transforming it into a clean data model, and surfacing it through live dashboards. The whole thing runs on Azure, with Python handling the ETL and Power BI on the front end.\n\nThe result: programme managers can now see impact metrics in real time. What used to take a week of manual work now happens automatically, every night.\n\n## The bigger lesson\n\nGood data infrastructure doesn't just save time. It changes the questions people ask. When you make insight accessible, people start asking *why* instead of just *what*. That's when technology starts to matter."
